{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5ef6ac0d-1d30-4ee5-8822-63d016980a3d","content":"","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"tooluse_z5gGeOrdcz3AxshPMF2k3c","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Enabling test hot reload"},"type":"function"},{"toolCallId":"tooluse_7wpiWR2hG3G69Am7uu2Yl8","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"/tmp/sv-1117840ab74f436494e106c4040cf449/TestProject.csproj","old_str":"    <TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>","new_str":"    <TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>\n    <TestingPlatformHotReloadEnabled>true</TestingPlatformHotReloadEnabled>"},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"edit the file at /tmp/sv-1117840ab74f436494e106c4040cf449/TestProject.csproj."}],"interactionId":"0bff3184-3312-4548-8d0f-10c862b670ef","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to enable hot reload (dotnet watch) for their test project without setting an environment variable every time. For `dotnet test`, hot reload is achieved via `dotnet watch test`. But the user might be referring to `DOTNET_WATCH` or `TESTINGPLATFORM_HOTRELOAD_ENABLED` or similar.\n\nActually, looking at this more carefully - with the modern Microsoft Testing Platform (`TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport`), hot reload for tests can be enabled via the `TESTINGPLATFORM_HOTRELOAD_ENABLED` environment variable, or via MSBuild properties.\n\nThe simplest approach to \"always enable\" hot reload without setting an environment variable every time would be to add the `TestingPlatformHotReload` MSBuild property to the `.csproj` file, or create a `Directory.Build.props` file, or use a `.runsettings` file.\n\n\nSo the best solution is to set `TestingPlatformHotReload` to true directly in the project file as an MSBuild property, which will automatically enable hot reload whenever running `dotnet test` without needing environment variables. For .NET 9+ with the Microsoft Testing Platform, the cleanest persistent approach is to add `<TestingPlatformHotReloadEnabled>true</TestingPlatformHotReloadEnabled>` to the csproj PropertyGroup, which sets hot reload as the default without needing environment variables or CLI flags each time. Alternatively, `dotnet watch test` works but requires changing the command itself. I'm second-guessing the exact property name here—the Testing Platform uses `dotnet test --hotreload` as a command-line flag, but I should verify whether there's a corresponding MSBuild property or if an environment variable like `TESTINGPLATFORM_HOTRELOAD` is the more reliable approach for persistent configuration. The simplest approach is to add the `TestingPlatformHotReloadEnabled` property directly to the project file, which will enable hot reload whenever `dotnet test` runs without needing environment variables or command-line flags each time.","outputTokens":1743},"id":"fff2a2d7-1f09-49eb-803b-f5f9a0739746","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:45:34.389Z","parentId":"c97ac1eb-a575-43cd-a84f-0fd8adc3fb34"}
